Laravel Mini Blog Setup on Laragon
Step-by-step guide to get a Laravel mini blog running locally using Laragon and MySQL.
Prerequisites

âœ… Laragon (Full version recommended: PHP, MySQL, Node.js)

âœ… Composer (comes with Laragon Full)

âœ… VS Code or another code editor

Step 1 â€“ Prepare Laragon
  Open Laragon.
  Ensure Apache and MySQL are running (green lights).
  Open WWW folder via Laragon â†’ opens C:\laragon\www.
  Remove any previous mini-blog folder or rename it (e.g., mini-blog-old).
  Optionally, delete the old blog_db database in Adminer or HeidiSQL.
  ğŸ’¡ Laragon auto-maps folders in www to .test domains like http://mini-blog.test/.

Step 2 â€“ Create a new Laravel project
  Open Laragon â†’ Menu â†’ Terminal â†’ CMD.
  Navigate to the www folder:
  cd C:\laragon\www
  composer create-project laravel/laravel mini-blog
  Open browser â†’ http://mini-blog.test/
  You should see the Laravel welcome page.
  If .test domain fails, try http://localhost/mini-blog/.

Step 3 â€“ Configure the Database
  Open Adminer or HeidiSQL via Laragon.
  Create a database:
  Name: blog_db
  Charset/Collation: utf8_general_ai_ci (or utf8mb4 if available)
  Open .env in VS Code and update:
  DB_CONNECTION=mysql
  DB_HOST=127.0.0.1
  DB_PORT=3306
  DB_DATABASE=blog_db
  DB_USERNAME=root
  DB_PASSWORD=
  âš ï¸ Uncomment lines if they have # at the start.

Step 4 â€“ Clear Cached Config
  php artisan config:clear
  Ensures Laravel reads the new database settings.

Step 5 â€“ Run Migrations
  cd C:\laragon\www\mini-blog
  php artisan migrate
  You should see:
    INFO  Preparing database.
    Creating migration table ... DONE
    Running migrations.
    0001_01_01_000000_create_users_table ... DONE
    0001_01_01_000001_create_cache_table ... DONE
    0001_01_01_000002_create_jobs_table ... DONE
    âœ… This confirms the database is connected and default tables are created.
